class Solution:
    def check(self, nums: List[int]) -> bool:
        n = len(nums)
        drops = 0
        for i in range(n):
            if nums[i] > nums[(i + 1) % n]:
                drops += 1
                if drops > 1:
                    return False
        return True

"""
Approach & Reasoning:
A sorted non-decreasing array after any rotation (including 0 rotations) will have at most one position where a larger element is followed by a strictly smaller one (the rotation point). All other consecutive pairs must satisfy nums[i] <= nums[i+1] (considering wrap-around for the last-to-first pair).

Count the number of such "drops" (nums[i] > nums[(i+1)%n]) while traversing the array once. If more than one drop exists, it cannot be a rotated sorted array. Otherwise it is valid.

Because duplicates are allowed (non-decreasing order), only strict decreases count as drops; equal elements are permitted anywhere.

The algorithm runs in linear time and uses constant extra space.

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(1)
"""
